<h1>Case-insensitive Autocomplete in Bash</h1>

<ul class="post-metadata">
	<li><time datetime="2010-05-27">27 May 2010</time></li>
	<li><a href="/tags/bash/" class="post-tag">bash</a></li>
</ul>

<p>I use auto complete on the command line all the time to avoid having to type the full name of a file. Love it. What I hate is how it’s case-sensitive in bash, so I can’t do <code>cd ~/desk</code> to go to the <code>~/Desktop</code> folder.</p>
<p>The fix for this is to use the shell input options file <strong>.inputrc</strong></p>
<p>Just set this one option and restart your shell:</p>
<pre class="language-bash" tabindex="0"><code class="language-bash"><span class="token builtin class-name">echo</span> <span class="token string">'set completion-ignore-case On'</span> <span class="token operator">>></span> ~/.inputrc</code></pre>
<p>If you happen to have a system wide inputrc settings (<code>/etc/inputrc</code>) and want it included then you should add the following to your .inputrc file:</p>
<pre><code>$include /etc/inputrc
</code></pre>

